Lindokuhle Xulu is taking a ride on a taxi and speaking to commuters and drivers. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - It's the start of the  three-day national taxi lekgotla in Boksburg in Ekurhuleni. The Transport department has confirmed the National Taxi Lekgotla will proceed as planned. READ: Public transport a priority: Ramaphosa Government is looking at different ways to formalise the industry. The national taxi alliance has indicated it won't attend the Lekgotla, saying it will be sidelined over the South African National Taxi Council (Santaco). Transport Minister Fikile Mbalula will be attending the lekgotla virtually as a precautionary measure. This after he attended an event graced by president Cyril Ramaphosa. READ: New union for taxi drivers launched The president is in self-isolation after a guest at a dinner he attended over the weekend tested positive for COVID-19. The three-day event, which starts today at Boksburg in eKurhuleni, is meant to find solutions to challenges facing the taxi industry and to formalise them.